<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. government has continued to sell millions of dollars worth of tritium 
-- crucial to the manufacture of nuclear weapons -- while saying that there may 
not be enough of the gas to continue production, it was reported. The only 
reactors able to make the rapidly decaying radioactive gas in the United States 
are at the Savannah River Plant in South Carolina, which was closed last April. 
The Energy Department has said there may be an urgent shortage by year end. But 
the New York Times, citing private experts, said the commercial sales to 
American and foreign companies indicate the situation may not be as serious as 
the department suggested. However, Troy Wade, acting assistant secretary of 
energy for defense programs, told the paper that the sales were small and that 
the possible shortage was not exaggerated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
