<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush moved on his promised review of U.S.-Soviet relations in a 
meeting at his weekend retreat in Kennebunkport, Me., with a group of academics 
in the field. Earlier, Bush and his wife, Barbara, marked the first Sunday of 
Lent by attending an hourlong service at the First Congregational Church where 
they were warmly welcomed. After lunch, the President met the professors from 
Harvard, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the Fletcher School of 
Law and Diplomacy and a fellow from the Brookings Institution who were brought 
in on short notice. Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the discussion was 
meant to be "open-ended and not designed to focus on any particular facet of 
East-West relations." Also at the meeting were National Security Adviser Brent 
Scowcroft and Lawrence S. Eagleburger, deputy secretary of state-designate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
