<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASKETBALL PAIRINGS; 
</P>
<P>
SADDLEBACK, MATER DEI ARE TOP-SEEDED TEAMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE KENNEDY, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Saddleback (24-1), the Sea View League champion, and Mater Dei (23-2), the 
Angelus League titlist, are the No. 1- and 2-seeded teams in the Southern 
Section Boys 5-AA Division basketball playoff pairings released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Saddleback has defeated Mater Dei twice this season. Loyola (20-2), the Del Rey 
League champion, is seeded third, and Lakewood, the Moore League titlist, is 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
First-round action begins Wednesday with the finals in all nine divisions 
scheduled for the week of Feb. 26-March 4. 
</P>
<P>
In the newly-adopted playoff format for the Southern Section, the first three 
teams in each league automatically qualified for the playoffs and were placed 
in divisions according to their size. 
</P>
<P>
Division 5-AA is for schools with an enrollment of at least 2,400; 5-A 
(2,000-2,399); 4-AA (1,750-1,999); 4-A (1,500-1,749); 3-A (1,000-1,499); 2-AA 
(750-999); 2-A (400-749); 1-A (150-399), and Small Schools (0-149). 
</P>
<P>
In addition, each league could submit other teams for playoff consideration, 
providing the teams had overall winning records. All at-large teams that were 
submitted for consideration were accepted, except in the 3-A, where the 32-team 
bracket was completely filled with automatic qualifiers. 
</P>
<P>
Schools were also allowed to move up one or more divisions if they gave notice 
before Jan. 9. Several schools, including Mater Dei, which went from 5-A to 
5-AA, and St. Paul, which went from 3-A to 4-A, took advantage. 
</P>
<P>
Here are remaining seeded teams, by division: 
</P>
<P>
5-A: 1. Pasadena (Pacific League No. 1); 2. Capistrano Valley (South Coast No. 
1); 3. Buena (Channel No. 2); 4. Irvine (South Coast No. 2). 
</P>
<P>
4-AA: 1. San Bernardino (San Andreas No. 1); 2. Glendora (Baseline No. 1); 3. 
Perris (Ivy No. 1); 4. El Modena (Century No. 1). 
</P>
<P>
4-A: 1. Dominguez (San Gabriel Valley No. 1); 2. St. Paul (Angelus No. 2); 3. 
Rio Mesa (Channel No. 1); 4. Barstow (San Andreas No. 2). 
</P>
<P>
3-A: 1. Rolling Hills (Bay No. 1); 2. La Canada (Rio Hondo No. 1); 3. Savanna 
(Orange No. 1); 4. Morningside (Ocean No. 1). 
</P>
<P>
2-AA: 1. Cabrillo (Los Padres No. 1); 2. Banning (Sunkist No. 1); 3. Cathedral 
(Santa Fe No. 1); 4. Whittier Christian (Olympic No. 2). 
</P>
<P>
2-A: 1. Santa Clara (Frontier No. 1); 2. Orange Lutheran (Olympic No. 1); 3. 
Paraclete (Desert-Inyo Large No. 1); 4. Cantwell (Santa Fe No. 2). 
</P>
<P>
1-A: 1. Pasadena Poly (Prep No. 1); 2. Southern California Christian (Arrowhead 
No. 1); 3. Bishop Diego (Tri-Valley No. 1); 4. Mission College Prep (Tri-County 
No. 1). 
</P>
<P>
SMALL SCHOOLS: 1. Hesperia Christian (Christian No. 1); 2. Pilgrim (Heritage 
No. 1); 3. Grace Community Christian (Westside No. 1); 4. Cal Lutheran (Academy 
No. 1). 
</P>
<P>
The Moore League was the biggest benificiary of the new policy to allow more 
than three teams from any one league into the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to Lakewood (20-6), Millikan (20-6) and Long Beach Jordan, the 
1-2-3 finishers in the league, Long Beach Poly (15-11), Long Beach Wilson 
(15-12) and Compton (13-11) advanced as at-large entrants. All of the school 
but Compton, which is 4-A, are in the 5-AA division. 
</P>
<P>
Four leagues, the Bay, Marmonte, Sea View and Whitmont, had five teams qualify. 
</P>
<P>
With only Saddleback and Mater Dei receiving byes in the 5-AA divsion, there 
are several interesting first-round matchups scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach Wilson is at St. Bernard (21-5), the Camino Real League champion, 
Long Beach Poly is at Lynwood (15-9), the San Gabriel Valley League runnerup, 
Leuzinger (15-11), an at-large entrants from the Bay League, is at Millikan and 
Long Beach Jordan is at Antelope Valley (16-8), the Golden League co-champion. 
</P>
<P>
Other first-round games of interest, in the 5-A, Beverly Hills (14-9) at Arroyo 
Grande (16-7); in the 4-AA, Servite (12-10) at Torrance (14-10); in the 4-A, 
West Torrance (12-12) at Bishop Amat (14-9); in the 3-A, Corona del Mar (15-9) 
at El Dorado (20-4), Western (16-6) at Sherman Oaks Notre Dame (16-8), 
Centennial (13-10) at Pomona (15-9); in the 2-AA, Miraleste (15-5) at Bell-Jeff 
(19-4); in the 2-A, Santa Maria St. Joseph (12-11) at Paraclete (20-2); and in 
the 1-A, Mary Star (16-7) at Brentwood (14-8). 
</P>
<P>
The only one of the nine playoff divisions that has a completely filled bracket 
is the 3-A. In that division there were 33 automatic qualifiers which 
necessitated a wild-card game to reduce the field to 32 teams. 
</P>
<P>
Norte Vista (13-10), the third-place team in the Mountain View League, travels 
to Yucaipa (9-14), the third-place team from the Sunkist League, tonight, with 
the winner playing at South Hills (19-5), Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Manual Arts (21-0), the defending state Division I champion and the only 
undefeated team in the City, is the top-seeded team in the boys' basketball 4-A 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
North Valley League champion Cleveland (20-2) is seeded second, followed by 
Crenshaw (17-2), the Southern League winner, and Carson (14-7), the Pacific 
League champion. 
</P>
<P>
Two coin flips on Tuesday will be necessary to finalize the pairings. Granada 
Hills (13-8) and Kennedy (12-8) are tied for third in the North Valley League 
and Palisades (9-11) and Fairfax (11-11) are tied for third in the Metro 
League. All first-round games are Friday. The City finals for both boys and 
girls in the 4-A and 3-A division are scheduled March 3 at the Sports Arena. 
</P>
<P>
Westchester (15-5), which lost twice to Manual Arts in Metro League play but 
has lost to no other City team, was unseeded and will play host to Banning 
(10-13). 
</P>
<P>
The Comets could play Crenshaw in the quarterfinals and Cleveland in the 
semifinals before a possible rematch against Manual Arts in the City final. 
</P>
<P>
In the 3-A division, Fremont (22-3) of the Central League is seeded No. 1 and 
either Los Angeles (14-8) or University (15-6), which tied for the Western 
League title, will be seeded No. 2. Wilson (17-5), the North East Valley 
champion is seeded third and North Hollywood (15-4), the Mid Valley League 
titlist, is seeded fourth. 
</P>
<P>
Three leagues, Eastern, Northwest and Northeast, play their final games 
Tuesday. Poly and Birmingham will have a playoff game, Wednesday at a neutral 
site to determine second place in the Valley East League. 
</P>
<P>
The pairings: 
</P>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION 
</P>
<P>
All games Wednesday at 7:30 unless indicated. Some sites to be determined 
</P>
<P>
