<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
FIRE DAMAGES MCFARLANE HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fire investigators today said an improperly installed fireplace caused a fire 
which did an estimated $75,000 damage to the home of former National Security 
Adviser Robert C. McFarlane. 
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out Sunday afternoon at the townhouse of McFarlane and his wife, 
Jonda, in the Georgetown section of the city. No one was injured in the blaze, 
which took 30 minutes to bring under control. McFarlane, who was White House 
national security adviser under former President Ronald Reagan, pleaded guilty 
last year to four misdemeanor counts of withholding information from Congress 
in connection with the Iran-Contra affair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
